nstitute what he calls an endarkenment that embraces decolonial spiritual knowledge. Highlighting how endarkenment practices challenge universal presumptions and reject the racializing and colonialist mission of enlightenment modernity, Snaza demonstrates the ways esoterism affirms a pluriversal worldview that reimagines what it means to live in a more-than-human world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplexStudy and teaching. 0aFeminism and literature. 0aFeminism and science. 0aFeminist spirituality. 0aFeminist theory. 0aOccultismxSocial aspects. 0aPostcolonialism. 0aQueer theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059103?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059103/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles